Digital Content Remediation Prioritization Framework
The Digital Content Remediation Prioritization FrameworkDownload Digital Content Remediation Prioritization Framework is designed to guide California State University (CSU) campuses in effectively prioritizing and expediting the remediation of digital content, ensuring compliance with Title II of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) by April 2026.

This comprehensive resource provides structured guidelines, actionable strategies, and recommended tools to assist campuses in developing or enhancing their internal accessibility processes. Title II mandates that public institutions ensure equal access to programs, services, and activities, making digital accessibility not only a legal obligation but a critical component of educational equity and inclusion.

Additional resources and examples can be found in the Files section of the Assets folder.

The Chancellor’s Office ATI is actively supporting this framework by providing targeted funding aligned with the strategies outlined in this document. For most campuses, this funding is intended to support the hiring of student assistants to enhance in-house capacity for digital content remediation. For fiscal year 2024–25, an Interagency Financial Transaction (IFT) was issued to all campuses on Friday, May 16.

About the ATI Digital Content Remediation Prioritization Framework
The Remediation Framework is designed to help campuses build sustainable, scalable approaches to digital content accessibility. Rather than treating remediation as a one-time task, the framework emphasizes developing internal workflows, often supported by trained student workers under staff supervision, to create long-term capacity and cultivate a culture of accessibility.

The framework encourages campuses to invest in student labor as a cost-effective alternative to vendor services, leveraging the training and tools available through the ATI Remediation Hub. While external vendors (such as Allyant) and emerging AI-based solutions play an important role in accelerating progress, full accessibility still requires manual remediation. AI may handle up to 80% of the workload, but the final 20% demands a human touch, which student teams can often address more affordably.

The initial round of funding is intended as seed support. Campuses are encouraged to use it to pilot sustainable models that align with systemwide best practices. A second round of funding will follow, with allocations informed by each campus’s demonstrated progress and commitment to long-term accessibility planning.

The remediation framework marks a significant step forward: it’s the first time the Chancellor’s Office has provided structured guidance and best practices for campus-level remediation efforts. Combined with advances in AI, this initiative provides a unique opportunity to make meaningful, lasting progress toward inclusive learning environments across the CSU.

